I have not done the verification of TDC with the dizzy thats in there, since
i do have a svda (according to #s and the old volks home, bosch # 231 170
093 is for 1800 L jetronic) but i can use this for the 78 FI,
so opinions please,
Q-keep the mechanical advance, with pertronix (part numbers not known yet)
OR put the svda in with points or svda with pertronix?
i figure if im gonna take it out i should put in the one thats best
suited..and no its not frozen advance!
and yes the plenum is good.
thanks Joe ( 78kombi)


On Wed, Feb 11, 2009 at 12:17 PM, Karl von Salzen wrote:

>  Ok, good.
>
> Now lets get back to basics and see where everything lines up.
>
> 1)  remove the 3/4 valve cover.
>
> 2)  get a remote starter button.  you want to rotate the engine in the
> direction of rotation.
>
> 3) I want you to watch the #3 valves as the engine rotates. #3 is left
> front.
>
> 4) As the engine turns, you will see the exhaust valve [end one] open then
> close and then instantly the intake will open and close.
>
> 5) Rotate the engine and just as the exhaust closes and the intake just
> starts to open, STOP. You want both valves to be at the rocking postition.
> Both closed but as you 'rock' the crankshaft back and forth, the rocker are
> will 'rock'.
>
> 6) At this point, stop. #1 will be exactly at TDC to fire. The dist rotor
> should be pointing to the index mark. And the most critical thing to look
at
> is the crank pulley mark. It will be dead on zero. It better be or you have
> a mis-marked pulley!  Or cam timing is off.....
>
>
>
>
> ------------------------------
>
> Date: Wed, 11 Feb 2009 09:13:49 -0500
> Subject: Re: timing
> From: spotop(-at-)gmail.com
> To: aufever(-at-)hotmail.com
>
>
> Karl.
> before work this morning i went to the bus and took off the rotor, i was
> able to turn the rotor about and inch clockwise and maybe an 1/8th inch
> Counter ..i put a few drops of mystery oil on the lil pad.. i dont think it
> is stuck , when turning it clockwise and let it go it sorta bounces back to
> its starting position.Joe
>
>
> On Mon, Feb 9, 2009 at 12:51 PM, Karl von Salzen
wrote:
>
>  Joe said:
>
> 78 2.0L F.I.
>  it was warm on sunday, so i broke out the timing light and compression
>  tester to what the deal is with my bus and cold starts, ( she'll run for a
>  bout
>  8 seconds at high throttle when it first starts then winds down to what
>  sounds like a 3 cylinder sputter. if i feather the gas til shes warm shes
>  fine..)
>  so i believe my bus is supposed to be set to 7.5 btdc, and the bentley
> just
>  sux on this subject..
>  so at idle its at 28 btdc ?! i tried to spin it forward til it read 7.5
> but
>  the bus just wanted to die. so i put it back to 28 btdc.
>  it was advancing well by about 10 -15 degrees when pulled on the throttle
>  cable..
>  so does this mean someone put the dist in 180 to where its supposed to be
>
> -------------------------------------------------------------------------
>
> NO..... it means your centrifugal advance is frozen fully advanced.  The
> advance you get when you open the throttle is vacuum advance.
>
> Get some rust penetrent and carb scleaner spray.  NOT WD 40.  Get PB
> Blaster or Kroil or Wurth Rust Off. Even liquid Liquid Wrench in a bottle.
>
> Remove the dist cap. Grab the rotor and try to rotate either way. Probably
> no.
> Remove the rotor. Look in the center. See that light brown felt pad? You
> were supposed to put a few drops of oil there like during each oil change
> [but don't feel bad, no one else does either!].
> Take an ice pick and lift out that pad. Fill the opening with penetrent.
> Let it sit for a few minutes. Refill when it runs down.
> Get a rag and wrap it around the base of the distributor. The bottom has
> drain holes to let the liquids out.
> Put the rotor back on and try twisting again back and forth.
> Remove rotor, refill with penetrent. Let sit.
>
> When you finally get the rotor to move, use the carb spray down the hole to
> do the final clean up.
>
> Then put the pad back and wet it with engine oil.
>
>
>
